<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-661-316  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 661 316.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  July 5 1990 n1221 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Scope for change in the Crown courts. (the UK's Crown ProsecutionService plans to implement the Standard Case Operations casetracking system.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hill, Simon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK's Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) will replace an interimcourt case tracking system (CATS) with the Standard CaseOperations (SCOPE) system, which complies with the Government OpenSystems Interconnect Profile (GOSIP).andP;  When founded thefour-year-old CPS had to quickly implement a system to track casesfrom police custody to sentencing, deciding on a three-stepinformation technology strategy (IT).andP;  The steps are quickstart aninterim system, develop a national open-standard CPS system' (ie,SCOPE), and coordination of IT across the entire UK criminaljustice system.andP;  The UNIX-based SCOPE will be the CPS's coresystem, linking 1,100 terminals in 120 UK branches.andP;  TheCoordination of Computerization in the Criminal Justice SystemInitiative body will link SCOPE to the Lord Chancellor's CrownElectronic Support Team systems and Home Office's magistratescourt Standard Specification system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DevelopmentLaw EnforcementLegal ApplicationsAutomationComputer SystemsSystem DesignTracking SystemsGreat Britain. Crown Prosecution Service.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>